{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12994"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12994"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.13,0.05,0.56,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56494"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5431"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42045"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1590"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"13217"},{"type":"tags","id":"13220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15995"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44142"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56494"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of fever and diffuse abdominal pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He recovered from COVID-19 three weeks ago. He has not travelled recently and his diet has been unchanged. He is of African descent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. A generalised, non-blanching macular rash is noted. There is widespread abdominal tenderness without guarding or rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is admitted for further management. Twelve hours after admission his condition deteriorates. He is anuric and confused. His blood pressure is 76/50 mmHg, pulse 147/min and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. His laboratory results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECardiac Troponin I: 64 ng/L (\u0026lt;26)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein: 49 mg/dL (\u0026lt;3)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESodium: 128 mmol/L (133-144)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlbumin: 28 g/L (33-48)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 19 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (3.5-11)\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELymphocytes: 0.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (1.5-4)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENeutrophils: 16.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (1.7-7)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 114 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-450)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ED-dimer: 3.2 mg/L (\u0026gt;0.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EeGFR: 32 mL/min/1.73m2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood culture and microscopy: No growth or micro-organisms can be seen.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Kawasaki disease","Toxic shock syndrome","Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis","Multisystem Inflammatory syndrome in children","Meningococcal septicaemia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EMultisystem Inflammatory Syndrome in Children (MIS-C)\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as Paediatric Inflammatory Multisystem Syndrome Temporally associated with SARS-CoV-2 (PIMS-TS)). Key features supporting this diagnosis include the recent history of COVID-19 infection, fever, abdominal pain, rash, shock, and laboratory findings of elevated inflammatory markers, cardiac involvement, and multiorgan dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMIS-C was first recognised in April 2020 during the COVID-19 pandemic. It is thought to be a post-infectious complication of SARS-CoV-2 infection, likely due to an abnormal immune response. The syndrome typically affects older children and adolescents. The pathophysiology is not fully understood, but it is believed to involve a dysregulated immune response leading to a cytokine storm. Treatment usually involves supportive care, immunomodulatory therapies such as intravenous immunoglobulin and corticosteroids, and in severe cases, intensive care support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki disease\u003C/strong\u003E shares some features with PIMS-TS, including fever, rash, and elevated inflammatory markers. However, Kawasaki disease typically affects younger children (usually under five years old) and is less likely to present with shock or significant gastrointestinal symptoms. The patient\u0027s age and the temporal association with COVID-19 make PIMS-TS more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic shock syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever, rash, and shock, similar to this case. However, toxic shock syndrome is typically associated with a focal bacterial infection, often due to \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E. The negative blood cultures and lack of a clear source of infection make this diagnosis less likely than PIMS-TS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpontaneous bacterial peritonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this case. While it can cause abdominal pain and fever, it typically occurs in patients with pre-existing ascites, usually due to liver disease. The multisystem involvement, rash, and cardiac dysfunction are not typical features of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningococcal septicaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever, rash, and shock. However, the non-blanching rash in meningococcal disease is typically petechial or purpuric, rather than macular as described here. The prominent abdominal symptoms, cardiac involvement, and recent COVID-19 infection are more suggestive of PIMS-TS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPIMS-TS is a newly recognised condition that typically occurs 2-6 weeks after SARS-CoV-2 infection. It is characterised by fever, multisystem inflammation, and organ dysfunction. The gastrointestinal symptoms, cardiac involvement (elevated troponin), and laboratory findings (elevated CRP, lymphopenia, thrombocytopenia) are all consistent with PIMS-TS. The condition can mimic other inflammatory conditions like Kawasaki disease or toxic shock syndrome, but the temporal association with COVID-19 and the patient\u0027s age make PIMS-TS the most likely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multisystem Inflammatory Syndrome in Children (MIS-C), also known as Paediatric Inflammatory Multisystem Syndrome Temporally associated with SARS-CoV-2 (PIMS-TS), is a newly characterised paediatric emergency syndrome that typically occurs 2-6 weeks after COVID-19 infection.","PIMS-TS can present with features that overlap with Kawasaki disease and toxic shock syndrome, but typically affects older children and adolescents.","Key features of PIMS-TS include fever, gastrointestinal symptoms, cardiac dysfunction, and elevated inflammatory markers."],"references":["Ross A, Shoff HW. Toxic Shock Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Sep 2. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459345/","Paediatric inflammatory multisystem syndrome (PIMS-TS) following SARS-COV-2 infection: Diagnosis and management. In: WA Health Clinical Practice Guidelines [Online]. Cited 2023 Jul 17. Available at: https://pch.health.wa.gov.au/For-health-professionals/Clinical-Practice-Guidelines/Paediatric-Inflammatory-Multisystem-Syndrome","Opoka-Winiarska V, Grywalska E, Roli\u0144ski J. PIMS-TS, the New Paediatric Systemic Inflammatory Disease Related to Previous Exposure to SARS-CoV-2 Infection-\u0022Rheumatic Fever\u0022 of the 21st Century? Int J Mol Sci. 2021 Apr 26;22(9):4488. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33925779/","Advice for clinicians: Paediatric inflammatory multi system syndrome temporally associated with SARS-COV-2 (PIMS-TS). In: AHPPC [Online]. Cited 2023 Jul 17. Available at: https://ncirs.org.au/advice-for-clinicians-PIMS-TS"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42045"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12994"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42045"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-20T22:15:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-21T08:02:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5431"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56494"}}},"meta":